<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="34" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1436,976,1402]" pageId="1" pageNumber="34">
One problem in revising 
<taxonomicName box="[446,521,976,1001]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Pipiza" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="34" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[446,521,976,1001]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="34">Pipiza</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is the large group of taxa described from 
<collectingCountry box="[1018,1101,976,1002]" name="Russia" pageId="1" pageNumber="34">Russia</collectingCountry>
: 
<taxonomicName authority="Violovitsh" authorityName="Violovitsh" box="[1112,1342,976,1002]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Pipiza" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="34" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="aurea">
<emphasis box="[1112,1209,976,1001]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="34">P. aurea</emphasis>
Violovitsh
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="Violovitsh" authorityName="Violovitsh" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Pipiza" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="34" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="convexifrons">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="34">P. convexifrons</emphasis>
Violovitsh
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="Violovitsh, P." authorityName="Violovitsh, P." box="[402,785,1016,1042]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Pipiza" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="34" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="magnomaculata">
<emphasis box="[402,620,1016,1041]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="34">P. magnomaculata</emphasis>
Violovitsh, 
<emphasis box="[765,785,1016,1041]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="34">P.</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
m u t i n i Violovitsh, 
<emphasis box="[1014,1131,1016,1041]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="34">P. n i e l s e n i</emphasis>
Violovitsh, 
<taxonomicName authority="Violovitsh" authorityName="Violovitsh" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Pipiza" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="34" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tristis">
<emphasis box="[1280,1376,1016,1041]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="34">P. tristis</emphasis>
Violovitsh
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Violovitsh (Violovitsh 1988)" authorityName="Violovitsh (Violovitsh" authorityYear="1988" box="[287,758,1056,1082]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Pipiza" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="34" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tuvinica">
<emphasis box="[287,410,1056,1081]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="34">P. tuvinica</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation box="[418,758,1056,1082]" pageId="1" pageNumber="46" refString="Violovitsh, N. A. (1988) Kratkii obzor Palearkticeskih vidov roda Pipiza Fallen (Diptera, Syrphidae). Taksonomia i ekologiya zhivotnykh Sibiri. Novye i maloizvestnye vidy fauny Sibiri. Novosibirsk, Nauka, Sibirskoe predprirastie RAN, 20, 108 - 126. [in Russian]" type="journal article">
Violovitsh (Violovitsh 
<number box="[686,749,1056,1082]" pageId="1" pageNumber="34" value="1988.0">1988</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
. Original descriptions are unfortunately often incomplete. Studies of some available material (e.g. Finnish Museum of Natural History) showed that at least 
<emphasis box="[1291,1383,1096,1121]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="34">P. a u re a</emphasis>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[151,369,1136,1161]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Pipiza" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="34" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="magnomaculata">
<emphasis box="[151,369,1136,1161]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="34">P. magnomaculata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(described from Russian Far East) belong to the species group analysed in this paper.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1436,976,1402]" pageId="1" pageNumber="34">
The 
<taxonomicName box="[250,449,1176,1201]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Pipiza" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="34" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="luteitarsis">
<emphasis box="[250,449,1176,1201]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="34">Pipiza luteitarsis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group, is characterized by the smooth hind femora without a pair of ventral, longitudinal ridges at the distal end (
<figureCitation box="[496,581,1216,1242]" captionStart="FIGURES 12, 13" captionStartId="4.[151,269,1104,1128]" captionTargetBox="[195,1393,669,1075]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[183,1404,665,1080]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 12, 13. Hind femur of male, ventral view. 12. Pipiza luteibarba n. sp.; 13. Pipiza festiva; lr – longitudinal ridge. Scale 1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/183305/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="34">
Fig. 
<number box="[551,581,1216,1242]" pageId="1" pageNumber="34" value="12.0">12</number>
</figureCitation>
) and ventral part of basoflagellomere reddish (
<figureCitation box="[1131,1246,1216,1242]" captionStart="FIGURES 4 – 9" captionStartId="3.[151,269,1919,1943]" captionTargetBox="[253,1341,349,1886]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[235,1352,336,1895]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 4 – 9. Antenna, lateral view. 4, male, 5, female, Pipiza luteibarba n. sp.; 6, male 7, female, Pipiza luteitarsis; 8, male, 9, female, Pipiza accola. Scale 1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/183303/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="34">
Figs. 
<number box="[1198,1246,1216,1242]" pageId="1" pageNumber="34" value="6.5" valueMax="9.0" valueMin="4.0">4–9</number>
</figureCitation>
). The main synapomorphic characters of this species group were found in the structure of male genitalia. Lower gonocercus of hypandrium is very short, about 
<number box="[566,577,1296,1322]" pageId="1" pageNumber="34" value="1.0">1</number>
/ 
<number box="[589,604,1296,1322]" pageId="1" pageNumber="34" value="3.0">3</number>
length of theca (
<figureCitation box="[803,891,1296,1322]" captionStart="FIGURES 19, 20" captionStartId="6.[151,269,1088,1112]" captionTargetBox="[193,1400,199,1056]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[160,1427,194,1064]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 19, 20. Male genitalia of Pipiza luteibarba n. sp. 19. lateral view; 20. dorsal view of epandrium; th – theca of hypandrium; b – basale of epandrium; lgc – lower gonocercus; ugc – upper gonocercus; sl - semicircular lobe of surstylus. Scale 0.1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/183307/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="34">
Fig. 
<number box="[858,891,1296,1322]" pageId="1" pageNumber="34" value="19.0">19</number>
</figureCitation>
: lgc). In other species of genus 
<taxonomicName box="[1265,1340,1296,1321]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Pipiza" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="34" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1265,1340,1296,1321]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="34">Pipiza</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, hypandrium always has long lower gonocercus, in lateral view it is about 
<number box="[957,970,1336,1362]" pageId="1" pageNumber="34" value="3.0">3</number>
/ 
<number box="[979,994,1336,1362]" pageId="1" pageNumber="34" value="4.0">4</number>
length of theca (
<figureCitation box="[1197,1286,1336,1362]" captionStart="FIGURES 27, 28" captionStartId="11.[151,269,1150,1174]" captionTargetBox="[254,1335,324,1114]" captionTargetId="figure@11.[240,1346,314,1126]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="FIGURES 27, 28. Male genitalia of Pipiza festiva. 27. lateral view; 28. dorsal view of epandrium; th – theca of hypandrium; lgc – lower gonocercus. Scale 0.1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/183311/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="34">
Fig. 
<number box="[1253,1286,1336,1362]" pageId="1" pageNumber="34" value="27.0">27</number>
</figureCitation>
: lgc). The 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Pipiza" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="34" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="luteitarsis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="34">P. luteitarsis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group comprises four species in the West Palaearctic.
</paragraph>
